      "abstract": "Abstract Abstract This paper presents a substantivist construal of discourse ethics, which claims that we should see our engagement in public deliberation as expressing and elaborating a substantive commitment to basic moral ideas of solidarity, equality, and freedom. This view is different from Habermas\u2019s standard formalist defence of discourse ethics, which attempts to derive the principle of discursive moral justification from primarily non\u2010moral presuppositions of rational argumentation as such. After explicating the difference between the substantivist and the formalist construal, I defend the former by showing that it is not only intuitively compelling, but also particularly well equipped for addressing four important objections recently levelled against discourse ethics and its political applications (Rawls\u2019s concern that it lacks substantive guidelines, Gunnarsson\u2019s challenge that it has not been proven to be superior to alternative moral conceptions such as utilitarianism, Scanlon\u2019s complaint that it lacks an account of moral motivation, and Galston\u2019s and Young\u2019s worries that it could lead to political practices of cultural imposition). I conclude by pointing out some consequences of the previous discussion for the future of Critical Theory. Keywords: discourse ethicsdeliberative democracyHabermasRawlssubstanceprocedure Notes I thank Arash Abizadeh, Jeffrey Flynn, Matthias Fritsch, John Kerkhoven, and referees for IJPS for comments and suggestions on earlier drafts of this paper. Research for this paper was supported by grants from the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council of Canada and the Fonds Qu\u00e9becois de la Recherche sur la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 et la Culture. 1 See Habermas, 1990a \u2014\u2014. 1990a. \u201c\u2018Discourse Ethics: Notes on a Program of Philosophical Justification\u2019\u201d. In Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action, Edited by: Habermas. 43\u2013115. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. C. Lenhardt and S. Weber Nicholsen [Google Scholar]: pp. 86, 92\u20133, and 96\u20137; 1998a \u2014\u2014. 1998a. \u201c\u2018A Genealogical Analysis of the Cognitive Content of Morality\u2019, in J. Habermas\u201d. In The Inclusion of the Other, Edited by: Cronin, C. and De Greiff, P. 3\u201346. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. [Google Scholar]: pp. 43\u20135. My reconstruction is slightly different from the formulation in Habermas (1990a \u2014\u2014. 1990a. \u201c\u2018Discourse Ethics: Notes on a Program of Philosophical Justification\u2019\u201d. In Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action, Edited by: Habermas. 43\u2013115. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. C. Lenhardt and S. Weber Nicholsen [Google Scholar]: p. 96), which goes as follows: \u2018(1) A definition of a universalization principle that functions as a rule of argumentation. (2) The identification of pragmatic presuppositions of argumentation that are inescapable and have a normative content. (3) The explicit statement of the normative content (e.g. in the form of discourse rules). (4) Proof that a relation of material implication holds between steps (3) and (1) in connection with the idea of justification of norms\u2019. Steps 2 and 3 in this formulation are put together in step 2 in my formulation. The assumption about the \u2018idea of justification of norms\u2019 which Habermas mentions as an auxiliary hypothesis in step 4 is mentioned in my reconstruction as step 3. These changes do not affect the content of Habermas\u2019s proof, and make more explicit the importance of the assumption of a certain view of the justification of norms. 2 (U) \u2018operationalizes\u2019, at the level of moral argumentation, what Habermas calls the general principle of discourse ethics (or of the discourse theory of morality) (D), according to which \u2018Only those norms can claim to be valid that meet (or could meet) with the approval of all affected in their capacity as participants in a practical discourse\u2019 (Habermas, 1990a \u2014\u2014. 1990a. \u201c\u2018Discourse Ethics: Notes on a Program of Philosophical Justification\u2019\u201d. In Moral Consciousness and Communicative Action, Edited by: Habermas. 43\u2013115. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. C. Lenhardt and S. Weber Nicholsen [Google Scholar]: pp. 66, 93; see also 1998a \u2014\u2014. 1998a. \u201c\u2018A Genealogical Analysis of the Cognitive Content of Morality\u2019, in J. Habermas\u201d. In The Inclusion of the Other, Edited by: Cronin, C. and De Greiff, P. 3\u201346. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. [Google Scholar]: p. 41). The term \u2018operationalization\u2019 appears in Habermas (1998a \u2014\u2014. 1996. Between Facts and Norms, Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. W. Rehg [Google Scholar]: p. 42; 1996 \u2014\u2014. 1996. Between Facts and Norms, Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. W. Rehg [Google Scholar]: p. 109; 2003a \u2014\u2014. 2003a. \u201c\u2018Rightness versus Truth: On the Sense of Normative Validity in Moral Judgments and Norms\u2019\u201d. In Truth and Justification, Edited by: Habermas. 237\u201375. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. trans. B. Fultner [Google Scholar]: p. 268). (U) operationalizes (D) in the domain of moral discourses, whereas a different principle of democratic legitimacy would operationalize (D) in the domain of political discourse. 3 Habermas (1998a \u2014\u2014. 1998a. \u201c\u2018A Genealogical Analysis of the Cognitive Content of Morality\u2019, in J. Habermas\u201d. In The Inclusion of the Other, Edited by: Cronin, C. and De Greiff, P. 3\u201346. Cambridge, Mass: The MIT Press. [Google Scholar]: p. 42). Habermas uses \u2018interests\u2019 in a wide sense, allowing for moral discourse to range over all kinds of reasons for action, including desires, needs, and conceptions of the good life. For an excellent discussion of Habermas\u2019s demand that norms protect \u2018common\u2019, \u2018general\u2019, or \u2018universalizab