al of justifiability to others\u2019 (p. 156). I take the force of that ideal to be itself in need of clarification, and argue that a reference to the project of justice (PJ), given the fact of disagreement (FD), provides the elucidation that we need. I agree with Kumar\u2019s (2003 Kumar, R. 2003. \u2018Reasonable Reasons in Contractualist Moral Argument\u2019. Ethics, 114(1): 6\u201337. [Crossref], [Web of Science \u00ae] , [Google Scholar]: p. 33) suggestion that Scanlon\u2019s contractualism is actually \u2018animated\u2019 by a substantive \u2018normative commitment\u2019 to the idea of \u2018individuals being able to live rationally self\u2010governed meaningful lives on terms of mutual respect for one another\u2019s value as persons\u2019. 24 So the way in which we should defend discourse ethics is by depicting (or elucidating) its own moral force as a \u2018normative package\u2019 including the ideas and the procedures working in tandem. If this package is the basis of morality, then we could not appeal to something else to justify it morally. At this point the spade should be turned. If Kant appeals to the \u2018fact of pure reason\u2019, and Habermas appeals to the \u2018fact of communicative rationality\u2019, we appeal to the fact of the normative package comprising the three substantive ideas and the discursive procedure under conditions of moral disagreement. If the sceptic really thinks that this package has no appeal, then we would not be able to convince her with moral arguments, but would have to turn to other forms of persuasion (based, for example, on prudential and strategic, or even existential, considerations). But then we would be answering a different question than the one with which we started, and our answer would not avoid the horns of Prichard\u2019s Dilemma. 25 A sense of justice includes moral ideal conceptions of persons and social life that constitute high\u2010order desires having motivational power alongside more specific, principl